<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sally</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">This doesn't happen all that much, but with certain zones it would be very helpful.<P>I am currently working on finishing up maps for Skyshrine. There are a couple parts of the zone that are vertically oriented, containing two or three overlapping areas.<P>Normally I like to have a map of the zone for each level, so the lines don't get confusing. For example, I created a "Sebilis" map for the top part of Sebilis and a "SebilisSewers" map for the lower part. I do a File-Open and open SebilisSewers if I'm down there.<P>For Skyshrine I will end up with at least three maps, perhaps four.<P>I was wondering if you guys could program a standard into SEQ for this. For example, if I had four maps for Skyshrine, my maps would be named:<P>  Skyshrine<BR>  Skyshrine2<BR>  Skyshrine3<BR>  Skyshrine4<P>"Skyshrine" would load upon entering the zone. Then to get to the other maps you would have a single keypress, for example, PgUp and PgDn. PgDn would cycle up in number, and PgUp would cycle backwards in number. For example, if you had just zoned in and Skyshrine loaded, and then entered the tower section of the zone, you would just press PgDn and SEQ would open the "Skyshrine2" map.<P>Not a huge thing, but would really make moving thru multiple maps more efficient.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nstalkerga</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">more of a load previous and load next.<BR>looking at the current file name and the placeholder in the alpha list?<P>good idea thou</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">deathinc</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I believe I read somewhere (sourceforge perhaps) that someone may/is add(ing) a vertical component to the map system in ShowEQ. I recall it having the ability to display lines that are +- so many units (z-axis) from your location. Perhaps looking into that would be a good idea?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sally</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yes, a load previous, load next, is what I think would work nicely.<P>I've only heard tidbits about the vertical filtering. Don't know if it was implemented. But even if it was, I'm not sure it would lend the kind of control over map display that I would desire.<P>I finished my Skyshrine map set. It turned out to be three maps. You *might* be able to get it to two maps, but I don't see the need. The zone is so spread out, there's little reason to be needing to see the far end of the zone on a separate level from where you are. The real need for three maps with Skyshrine is the tower, which has three levels. If you drew all three levels out on one map, it would be a disaster.<P>Skyshrine, Skyshrine2 and Skyshrine3 are on Mapfiend's site. Enjoy.<P>If you guys can do something with load previous and load next, that would be so cool.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ratt</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well... I don't see why the map/spawn filtering and map fade options don't cover what you want to do here.<P>If you can provide me with reasons why the three above options are not suitable, I'll look into it.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sally</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ratt,<P>Can you point me to a message thread that would give me some hints on how the "map/spawn filtering and map fade options" work? I'm not familiar with them.<P>Thanks.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ratt</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Not off the top of my head... <P>Do a search on these forums, or the SourceForge forums for depth filtering or just maps.<P>Something may or may not come up, I'm not sure...<P>Just a brief run down, however:<P>When you create a map in SEQ, it stores the Z location.  The map depth code uses that value to determine if the line should be displayed or not.<P>For instance, when I'm in OS and I turn on filtering and I'm hanging out in the Jail, all I see is the jail area and some other rooms across the zone that are on the same plane / elevation as the room I'm in.  I can do this for mobs as well.<P>You can increase/decrease the tolerance, revealing more or less of the upper/lower parts of the map at will.  <P>Fading will fade the map in and out as you acend or decend.<P>I can think of a _FEW_ places where this might not be suitable and a few circumstances where this might not be suitable... but for those few I don't know if it's worth the trouble to go through to put in a next/last option that probably wouldn't be used.<P>I'll try to answer any questions you may have, if I can.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sparr</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">forgive the lack of exactness.  load up any map created since like july 2000 (about when 3d lines went in) and hit "1" then "2".  that fill filter out any lines and mobs that are more than X units above you or Y units below you.  to change X and Y you use "5" and "6" and "8" and "9" i think, its all on one of the menus.  id like someone to put in a popup window to set them manually but it DOES work the way it is.  the default X and Y are too low, i usually raise X about 6 times and lower Y the same amount, with tweaking depending on the exact zone.  i think hitting "3" will change the map lines from just disappearing to where they fade off into the distance, not sure on that one.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">FrozenInTime</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Those options are held in the showeq.conf file.  I think by default they are 75 and 80.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sally</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hmmm...okay, I tried hitting "1" then "2" etc. as described above, with no effect. I looked at all the menus with nothing that looked like vertical filtering.<P>Can someone point me to the menu option where this is controlled?<P>I'm using 2.5 (although I thought I had upgraded thru CVS to 2.5.1), at least that's what is displayed on my terminal screen when I start up.<P>Like I said, hitting "1" then "2", or "5" and "6", does nothing.<P>Thanks</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">cpphack</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Try using the latest CVS version (2.5.4), though I believe even the latest tar version (2.5.3) will work with the Z-axis filtering.<P>Note that not all maps use this.  Maps created using the 2D "L" map lines won't show any changes when the map fade is used.  Maps created using the 3D "M" map lines will work.  (For example, Blackburrow.)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Andrew</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I added the map filtering feature.  3 does make it fade mode instead of appear-disappear.<BR>I haven't checked many of the recent CVS snapshots for inclusion of the feature so it may need to be checked.<BR>Yes it is in the conf file.  I think each tap of the increment keys is equal to 10 units.  It is an excelent feature.  Maybe this weekend I'll work on moving the map around a bit without having to go there.  (I especially want a "Center on target" feature.)  So, for my sake, keep the maps in one file and use the filtering.  (It's really cool to walk down steps and see the walls fade in etc.)<P>Andy</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
